Setting up train/test data

train_idx = sample(nrow(BTC_data), size = nrow(BTC_data) * 0.8)

BTC_train = BTC_data[train_idx, ]
BTC_test = BTC_data[-train_idx, ]

We will train the model on 80% of the data and test it on the other 20%

Variance inflation factor

We will now check for collinearity in our models. We expect there to be several collinear variables in our models considering some of our predictors are transformations of each other (e.g.price_change, Percent_Change, price_chng_max_abs_scale) We will consider any inflation factor \(> 5\) to be large

Fixing the collinearity issues with our models does not affect the 5-fold cross validation very much, but this is expected. Collinearity has a much stronger effect on parameter estimates than it does on accuracy. When a model has high collinearity, the variance of the paramters increases drastically. This increase in variance makes it much harder to prove the significance of your parameters. We mainly want to use our model for prediction, so this doesnt help us too much. However, it does improve our models ability to explain the response.

Lets use a stepwise search in order to get some other candidate models

We will select models using both AIC and BIC as our search criteria. We will also start off by doing a stepwise search using all available predictors

full_mod = glm(price_increase_next_day ~ . - X1, data = BTC_train, family = binomial)
full_step_aic = step(full_mod, direction = "both", trace = 0)
full_step_bic = step(full_mod, direction = "both", trace = 0, K = log(n))

Model Evaluation:

We will only look at the AIC models from the stepwise search. All of the models selected using BIC only have the intercept as a parameter. Therefore, we will not use these models. This makes some sense because BIC tends to penalize additional parameters more than AIC.

Model performance

We will create a function for making a confusion matrix of our results as well as calculating the accuracy

pred_table = function(glm_model) {
  predicted = ifelse(predict(glm_model, BTC_test) > 0, TRUE, FALSE)
  accuracy = mean(predicted == BTC_test$price_increase_next_day)
  tbl = table(predicted = predicted, actual = BTC_test$price_increase_next_day)
  list(model = glm_model$call, test_accuracy = accuracy, table = tbl)
}
table_full_step_aic = pred_table(full_step_aic)
table_glm4 = pred_table(glm4)
table_glm4_step_aic = pred_table(glm4_step_aic)
table_full_int_step_aic = pred_table(full_int_step_aic)

Creating a function for calculating the sensitivity and specificity of the model

get_sens = function(conf_mat) {
  conf_mat[2, 2] / sum(conf_mat[, 2])
}

get_spec =  function(conf_mat) {
  conf_mat[1, 1] / sum(conf_mat[, 1])
}

evaluate = function(table_list) {
  model = toString(table_list$model)
  data.frame(
    model = model,
    test_accuracy = table_list$test_accuracy,
    sensitivity = get_sens(table_list$table),
    specificity = get_spec(table_list$table))
}

ROC curves

Creating a function for plotting ROC curves

calc_roc = function(model, divisions = 10, plot = TRUE) {
  sens_vals = rep(0, times = divisions)
  spec_vals = rep(0, times = divisions)
  
  probs = predict(model, BTC_test, type = 'response')
  actual_T = sum(BTC_test$price_increase_next_day)
  actual_F = length(BTC_test$price_increase_next_day) - actual_T
  
  for (i in 0:divisions) {
    threshold = i * (1.0 / divisions)
    predictions = ifelse(probs > threshold, TRUE, FALSE)
    accuracy = mean(predictions == BTC_test$price_increase_next_day)
    tbl = table(predicted = predictions, actual = BTC_test$price_increase_next_day, useNA = 'always')
    sens_vals[i] = get_sens(tbl)
    spec_vals[i] = get_spec(tbl)
    
    
  }
  
  if (plot == TRUE) {
    par(bg = 'gray95')
    plot(y = sens_vals, x = (1 - spec_vals), type = 'p', main = 'ROC Curve', col = 'dodgerblue', xaxp = c(0, 1, 10), yaxp = c(0, 1, 10))
    grid(nx = 10, ny = 10)
    line_y = seq(from = 0, to = 1, by = 0.05)
    line_x = line_y
    lines(line_y ~ line_x)
  }
  
  else if (plot == FALSE) {
    list(sensitivities = sens_vals, specificities = spec_vals)
  }
}
calc_roc(full_step_aic, divisions = 200, plot = TRUE)

calc_roc(glm4, divisions = 200, plot = TRUE)

calc_roc(glm4_step_aic, divisions = 200, plot = TRUE)

calc_roc(full_int_step_aic, divisions = 200, plot = TRUE)

Revaluating accuracy

Many of our models have a high sensitivity and low specificity. Sensitivity is the true positive rate and specificity is the true negative rate. Therefore, our models are much better at predicting when the price will go up versus down. Lets see if changing the classification threshold helps improve the accuracy of these models.

Creating functions for finding the best accuracy

get_acc = function(model, threshold) {
  predictions = ifelse(predict(model, BTC_test, type = 'response') > threshold, TRUE, FALSE)
  accuracy = mean(predictions == BTC_test$price_increase_next_day)
  accuracy
}
best_acc = function(model, iterations) {
  accuracies = rep(0, times = iterations)
  thresholds = rep(0, times = iterations)
  for (i in 1:iterations) {
    thresh = i * 1 / iterations
    acc = get_acc(model, threshold = thresh)
    accuracies[i] = acc
    thresholds[i] = thresh
  }
  best_acc_ind = which.max(accuracies)
  list(Accuracy = accuracies, Threshold = thresholds, best_acc = accuracies[best_acc_ind], best_thres = thresholds[best_acc_ind])
}

Conclusion

Unfortunately, we were not able to find any models that could predict next-day price movement with sufficient accuracy. We know from previous workbooks that the price of bitcoin rose the next day roughly 54% of the time for this dataset. Our goal was to, at the very least, have higher accuracy than this percentage because we wanted a model that performs better than predicting TRUE for every single outcome. We were able to achieve this goal, but we did not beat it by much. Our best model full_step_aic has an accuracy of 57.19%. This is only 3.19 % higher than the 54% we wanted to beat.

Nonetheless, predicting the price of any crypto currency can be difficult due to the extreme volatility of the markets. With a simple google search, you can see that many people have tried and failed to predict the price of bitcoin. Others have had some success, but their models do not show consistent performance. Some people have been able to successfully predict the price of bitcoin on a very short time frame. They have even expanded these algorithms to be used for trading. However, the major issue seen with these models is that even when the algorithm can make profitable trades, the fees associated with those trades are higher than the profits themselves.

Regardless, the was a great learning experience, and Im excited to start working on potential improvements for this model!
